comment.narrative:
Targets 1:
• Identify the AccLab’s key frontier challenge (focus area) by understanding the major challenges facing South Africans and the South African government
• Identify how the AccLab’s frontier challenges are currently being addressed by the CO’s programmes and how these can be accelerated;
• Identify points of collaboration and cohesion between CO programmes/projects.

Targets 2:
• Ethnographic and field research findings translated into learning and action for the acceleration lab activities; 
• Designing and implementing methodology for intaking indigenous knowledge and local solutions, consolidating, screening and further describing incoming ideas;
• Advise on the accelerator lab’s experiment portfolio to ensure experiments are designed based on people’s knowledge, behaviours and peer to peer methods of managing and diffusing knowledge about sustainable development issues;
• Lead communication efforts and proactively use blog and social media to share findings from field research.

Targets 3:
• At least one horizon scanning study for continuous communication of any emerging trends to the Country Office and partners ; 
• New relationships and networks developed for partnerships on emerging projects; 
• Amount resources mobilised for AccLab projects; 
• A collective intelligence study to inform projects. 

Targets 4:
• A framework developed to capture the learning from the experiments that supports critical reflection; 
• Results from the testing of prototypes translated into proposals informing decisions on next steps, e.g. scaling options.

Targets 5:
• A successful cycle of sense-explore-test to scale successful solution(s) using the most suitable methods, as applicable to the solution/innovation type;
• Relationships established with suitable partners (both internal and external to UNDP) to scale up the successful solutions.

Targets 1:
• Key frontier challenges identified, including Youth Unemployment and the Food, Water, Energy Nexus; 
• Acceleration activities identified through sense making, continuous communication, and active collaboration; 
• Collaborated on multiple projects internally, including collaborations with the programme areas Inclusive Growth and Energy and Environment. 

Targets 2:
• Learning and actions identified through field research in Limpopo, KwaZulu Natal, Eastern Cape, and Northern Cape;
• Developed initial version of fieldwork guide to identify solutions and capture novel information; 
• Experiments informed by solutions mapping and ethnographic insights; 
• Developed 8 blogs, 15 press releases, and multiple posts on social media and Microsoft Teams networks. 

Targets 3:
• Completed horizon scanning on continuous basis (though the pandemic limited this exercise);
• Network of over 50 stakeholders and potential partners developed;
• CSIR $476 000 (JSB), INR $150 000 (RRF), WRC $100 000 (Trac 3 and JSB), YoMobi $130 000 (RRF);
• 1 collective intelligence study designed.

Targets 4:
• Developed framework to capture learning from experiments;
• 13 innovations tested, and provided with scaling options and support.
13 innovations underwent experimentation using various Innovation methods included Multi-site trials, cluster randomised trials, prototyping, Pre-post tests, hybrid tests and adaptive trials. 

Targets 5:
• 16 innovations scaled after a successful cycle;
• 3 key relationships established to scale innovations, including the Water Research Commission, Tshimologong Innovation Precinct, and the Institute for Natural Resources.
